<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n09155j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n09" href="#n09155j">N09 (VI.B.1)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n09all.htm#n09155j"> 155(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> clothe the dead</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Worse than that, they say only <mark>the dead deserve to be clothed</mark>, this obviously to hide their offensive corruption; hence the verb <i>fwala</i>, &ldquo;to dress,&rdquo; is the same root as &ldquo;to die.&rdquo; Thus, at the back of the black man&apos;s brain, &ldquo;dress,&rdquo; as a technical term means &ldquo;deformity hiding,&rdquo; hence this cheeky mob of nearly-naked smilers boasting they were (&ldquo;look at us!&rdquo;) formed not deformed. <small> Dan Crawford, <a name="BTLG1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#BTLG1"><cite title="source">Back to the Long Grass</cite></a> (1923) 168</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
